(1 inline comment)

I have one inline question, but also, should we add a change to glance.db.sqlalchemy.api update image path to show how we are expecting the location object to look like. Also maybe some test showing example of call to db api. I like this idea I think it applies to image table too, that way we can store more complex metadata for the image that will help with activation logic

Patch Set 2:

@David Peraza, IMO, we store metadata to location table is enough but not need it for image table, since: 1. for those 'common' metadata of an image, it can be sotred into 'image_properties' table, I conside it was designed for store that. 2. for those location related metadata of an image, it should be stored into 'image_locations' table. So, for the complex activation logic support you moentioned, you/user should store the customized key/value to 'image_properties' table as the image property.

Patch Set 2:

thanks for response Zhi Yan Liu	that is what we do today, but for example, we have stored properties with json or more comples json with xml text and that makes a bit harder, we need to worry about escape chars and such. We could always mime encode that, but it would be nice to store as pickle object we can just unpickle without worry about escape and double escape etc. Did not mean to discuss this right on this patch but if folks don't mind i'm fine with it.

Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Hi John,

This change looks good to me (+2), but like David I'm a bit unsure of all its implications. So while I don't think this patch needs any changes, I'd like to see more of how dependent patches would make use of the new column before we go ahead with this one.

Thanks!

After reviewing the patch that uses this new location metadata, I have to say I'm not in love with using "anything pickleable" as the storage format. The dependent branch looks like it will print out in the api any python object that is json-serializable as the metadata, so None, strings, ints, dicts, lists, etc. Is there any way for us to more forcefully restrict location metadata to be "just" a particular type of format? Enforcing it as a dictionary, like image properties, seems like it could enforce more sanity.
